Tomorrow, Tuesday 9/8 is our first day of school!
A Cohort will be in-person Tues/Wed this week and B Cohort in-person Thurs/Friday.

On short weeks, all-virtual Wednesdays are converted to in-person days to maximize in-person instructional days. Please see the District calendar for details.

Looking forward to welcoming back our students!

post_text:
Attention New Registrations

If you are missing any of the following paperwork, please send in with your child on their first day of school, or drop off at school. There is a drop box outside the main entrance. Registration is not complete without the proper paperwork and can exclude your child from school.

Immunization records
Physical
Birth certificate
Proofs of residency
Custody papers

If you have any questions, please call Elementary #1's main office.

Thank you for your cooperation.

Statement from Superintendent Dr. David Salvo:

Although Governor Murphy has given school districts the option to go to a full remote learning schedule, Middle Township Public Schools will continue with its plan on implementing a Hybrid Schedule. Our plan balances the safety of our students and staff with the desire to return to school. Student schedules will be mailed within the next week. Please visit our district website for all restart of school information. Thank you.

Elementary #1 Families,

post_text:
IMPORTANT
Statement from Superintendent Dr. David Salvo:
On behalf of the Middle Township School District, we express our sincere condolences to the family of Mr. George Floyd. As a nation, we strive to seek justice in a peaceful manner. Martin Luther King Jr. once stated, “Violence brings only temporary victories; violence, by creating many more social problems than it solves, never brings permanent peace.”

We are committed to providing a safe and supportive school environment in which our students understand that their lives and voices are valued, regardless of race, ethnicity or gender. Above all, we respect and support each other.

We all need to have courageous conversations that promote and enhance equality in our community. As Winston Churchill said, “Courage is what it takes to stand up and speak; courage is also what it takes to sit down and listen.”
text:
IMPORTANT
Statement from Superintendent Dr. David Salvo:
On behalf of the Middle Township School District, we express our sincere condolences to the family of Mr. George Floyd. As a nation, we strive to seek justice in a peaceful manner. Martin Luther King Jr. once stated, “Violence brings only temporary victories; violence, by creating many more social problems than it solves, never brings permanent peace.”

We are committed to providing a safe and supportive school environment in which our students understand that their lives and voices are valued, regardless of race, ethnicity or gender. Above all, we respect and support each other.

We all need to have courageous conversations that promote and enhance equality in our community. As Winston Churchill said, “Courage is what it takes to stand up and speak; courage is also what it takes to sit down and listen.”

post_text:
HAPPY TEACHER APPRECIATION DAY!
Today and everyday we appreciate our amazing teachers. They inspire, encourage, support and love their students, whether in or out of school. During these extraordinary times, our teachers have gone above and beyond. We know our teachers will continue to provide their students an exceptional educational experience through Remote Learning platforms. We recognize that this transition has not been without its challenges. So on this Teacher Appreciation Day, we would like to take this opportunity to THANK all of YOU - the parents, grandparents, guardians and caregivers. Please know that we appreciate all your efforts and we are grateful for your support. Even though we're apart, TOGETHER we will ensure our Elementary #1 students, your children, succeed and know how special they are to us! #allinthistogether Middle Township Elementary #1 Preschool

Cape May Court House Vol. Fire Company
April 28 at 8:57 PM ·

The volunteer fire companies of Middle Township will be hosting a food drive Saturday, May 9th (Rain date is May 10th).Covid-19 has affected us all and now more then ever our local food banks need help feeding those in need. Fire trucks will be visiting streets and neighborhoods from 10am to 2pm to collect donations. If you are able, please leave non-perishable food items at the end of your driveway. All items collected will be distributed to our local food banks to support our friends and neighbors in need.

There is a huge demand for cereal, pasta, jars of spaghetti sauce, dry milk, peanut butter, jelly, paper products and other non-perishables. Every little bit counts, making a difference for all of us in Middle Township.

Even if you are unable to donate, come out and wave to cheer us on. If we miss your donation please bring items to your local Fire House. All 5 fire houses (Court House, Swainton, Goshen, Green Creek and Rio Grande) will be open from 2pm to 3pm on Saturday for drop offs. Thank you in advance for your love and support.

Day 39

Tonight we honor the Healthcare Heroes fighting this battle 24/7 with grit, determination, ingenuity and compassion.

Since we can't gather in the parking lot and our banner plane got grounded, how about this....

Every time you drive by Cape Regional Hospital, toot your horn? Small and constant shouts that say, "We're thinking of you. We support you. We honor you. THANK YOU."

shared_text:
National Park Service
April 18 at 8:20 AM ·

Kick off #NationalParkWeek with National Junior Ranger Day! The Junior Ranger Program is a great way to explore national parks. You can learn about nature sounds, night skies, or even the Transcontinental Railroad! You'll also learn why national parks matter and how you can be a part of the team that helps keep parks healthy.

We don't care what age you are—just "explore, learn, and protect" your national parks online and become an official Junior Ranger! Look for the virtual badges you can print out and post on your refrigerator. Learn more at https://www.nps.gov/kids/junior-ranger-online.htm

#FindYourVirtualPark #JuniorRangerDay

Middle Township Recreation & Tourism
April 4 at 6:09 PM ·

Middle Township Youth Wrestling is staying SAFE and is not stuck at home to protect our wrestlers and our families. We all need to stay home to protect the first responders, the medical professionals, grocery store workers, truck drivers, and all the others who have no choice but to work outside the home. MTYWA encourages you to join us in making the commitment to STAY HOME!! Let’s flatten this curve!! Stay home, stay healthy, and stay positive. We will beat this together and we will be back on the mat!! #MTWYA #justwrestle #stayhome

post_text: Mr. McGowen's second-grade class had their first "Think Outside the Box" Thursday on Zoom with a special visitor, Mrs. Gibboni! Mr. McGowen gave each student this picture. Then they drew what they thought the shape was! The students drew a baseball field, a house, curtains, robots, smile faces, a glass of water, pizza, mushrooms and more! Mr. McGowen is curious to know what you think the shape is? Draw the shape on a paper and get creative. You can even share your picture in the comments below!!

Mr. McGowen is curious to know what you think the shape is? Draw the shape on a paper and get creative. You can even share your picture in the comments below!!

Good morning Elementary #1 students and families. Please visit our homepage to find your child's "Home Instruction" lessons. Click the “staff” link for the staff directory. There you will find your child’s teacher in the directory. Click on the teacher’s name to access their website.
You can access home instruction lessons/activities by clicking the tab labeled, “Home Instruction in Case of School Closing.” Special Area teachers (Art, Gym, Library, Music, STEM and Book Chat) and Support Services (BSIP, Speech, and ESL) individual websites can also be found under the staff directory. post_text: Good afternoon parents this is Dr. David Salvo Superintendent of Schools. After consultation with the County Health Department, Middle Township Public Schools will be closed effective Tuesday, March 17 through March 30st. We plan to reopen March 31st but that will be determined, after consultation, with the County Health Department. On Monday students will collect all their personal belongings to take home for the school closing. Please check our district webpage and social media sites for specific home instruction procedures for each school. For those families that do not have the technology to complete the home instruction, please call the school and arrangements will be made. Essential staff will be working in the buildings throughout the closing. If you have any questions during the closing please call your child’s school. We will do our best to update you, throughout the closing, on our social media cites. Please be safe and thank you for your cooperation.

To wrap their project up, students had some hands on experience by making their own pizza, using toppings that are popular in our country!

post_text: Our Kindergarten thru Second Grade students will get a chance to meet a variety of turtles that are native to New Jersey, as well as explore various hands-on turtle artifacts. This opportunity is brought to us by The Wetlands Institute, Traveling Environmental Education Program. Classes will dive into topics such as: turtle anatomy, natural history, behaviors, adaptations, life cycles, and more. Students will also learn about our Diamondback Terrapin Conservation Project and get some quality time with live adult terrapins. Although students do not touch the live turtles, there are plenty of opportunities to view these amazing animals.

post_text: Congratulations Mr. Farrow for your well deserved honor and recognition!
shared_text:
Middle Township Middle School added a new photo to the album: 2019-2020 Announcements and Information.
December 16, 2019 at 8:54 PM ·

Middle Township Middle School’s own David Farrow is the 2020 recipient of the NJEA’s Judy Owens Spirit Award! This is well deserved. Dave is an advocate for ALL of his students (over 500 of them)! He is also a leader in our community. He brings the school and the community together in a variety of ways, but one of the strongest is the Community Conversation Circles he hosts with a FAST grant from NJEA. Dave encourages community members, faculty, and students to come together and talk about diversity in an open honest way to bring truth, healing, and understanding. He leads many school events as well. Thank you, Dave and congratulations!!! 🎈🎊🎉

Thank you in advance for your support of our library!

Elementary #1 is one of the drop off locations for the Annual Christmas Toy Drive event to benefit St. Christopher's Hospital for Children and The Ronald McDonald House. The Kyle Martin Brown Foundation collects and deliveries all the toys. We are happy to assist the foundation in memory of Kyle, who was a Middle Township student. Donations of new and unwrapped toys, for boys and girls of all ages, can be placed in the collection box located by the main office. Donations accepted until Tuesday, December 17th. Thank you!

The Kyle Martin Brown Foundation
November 27, 2019 at 3:47 PM ·

We will update as we add and collect the toys! Thank you for your continued support. #Kyletime #KylesCommunity #dogoodthings

post_text:
PAINT NIGHT FUN at ELEMENTARY #1
A festive and fun evening hosted by Middle Township High School art teacher, Karen Biederman, along with her talented students. Our second grade students spent time creating their own special holiday canvas. They also received a Santa Hat and were served pizza and a snack. A huge THANK YOU to Ms. Biederman and our high school friends for a wonderful time. We would also like to thank the Middle Township Education Association for sponsoring this family event!
